South African futures were higher on Friday after the JSE all share closed firmer for the first time in six sessions. Industrials and retailers buoyed market sentiment with banks and financials also gaining on positive US jobs data, which increased the likelihood of a US rate hike next week.The rand was at R13.1641 against the dollar in early evening trade from R13.3375.The JSE all share closed 0.7% up at 51,269.50 and the blue-chip top 40 added 0.8%. General retailers added 1.21% and industrials rose 1.15%. Banks were up 0.9% and platinums 0.47%. The gold index shed 2.37%.The all share ended the week 0.85% down but was still 1.22% up for the year.The Dow Jones was up 0.16% in early evening trade. European markets were firmer with the FTSE 100 up 0.65% and the German Dax gaining 0.17%.At 5.45pm, the local near-dated top-40 Alsi futures index was 0.76% higher at 44,261 points with 28,773 contracts traded from Thursday&rsquo;s 28,139.